\section{Structures of dipotassium rubidium citrate monohydrate, $\mathrm{K}_{2} \mathrm{RbC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, and potassium dirubidium citrate monohydrate, $\mathrm{KRb}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, from laboratory X-ray powder diffraction data and DFT calculations}
Department of Chemistry, North Central College, 131 S. Loomis, St., Naperville IL, 60540, USA. *Correspondence e-mail: \href{mailto:kaduk@polycrystallography.com}{kaduk@polycrystallography.com}

The crystal structures of the isostructural compounds dipotassium rubidium citrate monohydrate, $\mathrm{K}_{2} \mathrm{RbC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, and potassium dirubidium citrate monohydrate, $\mathrm{KRb}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, have been solved and refined using laboratory X-ray powder diffraction data, and optimized using density functional techniques. The compounds are isostructural to $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$ and $\mathrm{Rb}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, but exhibit different degrees of ordering of the $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{Rb}$ cations over the three metal-ion sites. The $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{Rb}$ site occupancies correlate well to both the bond-valence sums and the DFT energies of ordered cation systems. The $M \mathrm{O}_{6}$ and $M \mathrm{O}_{7}$ coordination polyhedra share edges to form a threedimensional framework. The water molecule acts as a donor in two strong charge-assisted $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} \cdots \mathrm{O}$ hydrogen bonds to carboxylate groups. The hydroxyl group of the citrate anion forms an intramolecular hydrogen bond to one of the central carboxylate oxygen atoms.

\section{Chemical context}
A systematic study of the crystal structures of Group 1 (alkali metal) citrate salts has been reported in Rammohan \& Kaduk (2018). The study was extended to lithium metal hydrogen citrates in Cigler \& Kaduk (2018), to sodium metal hydrogen citrates in Cigler \& Kaduk (2019a), to sodium dirubidium citrates in Cigler \& Kaduk (2019b), to dilithium potassium citrate (Cigler \& Kaduk, 2019c), to lithium dipotassium citrate monohydrate in Cigler \& Kaduk (2020), and to potassium rubidium hydrogen citrate in Gonzalez et al. (2020). These compounds represent further extensions to potassium rubidium citrates. The crystal structure of $\mathrm{K}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, Cambridge Structural Database refcode ZZZHVI* has been reported multiple times (Burns \& Iball, 1954; Carrell et al., 1987), and the structure of $\mathrm{Rb}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$ has been reported by Rammohan \& Kaduk (2017).

