\section{Synthesis and crystallization}
Dipotassium rubidium citrate monohydrate, (I), was synthesized by adding stoichiometric quantities of $1.382 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~K}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ (Sigma-Aldrich) and $1.154 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{Rb}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ (Sigma-Aldrich) to a solution of $2.03 \mathrm{~g}$ citric acid monohydrate (10.0 mmol, SigmaAldrich) in $10 \mathrm{ml}$ of water. After the fizzing subsided, the clear solution was dried in a $403 \mathrm{~K}$ oven to yield a white solid. Potassium dirubidium citrate monohydrate, (II), was synthesized in the same way starting from $0.691 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{K}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ and $2.309 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Rb}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$.

\section{Refinement}
Crystal data, data collection and structure refinement details for (I) are summarized in Table 7 (Fig. 7). To minimize Rb fluorescence, the pulse height discriminator lower level of the $\mathrm{X}^{\prime}$ Celerator detector was raised from the default $39.0 \%$ to $51.0 \%$. The structure was solved with $F O X$ (Favre-Nicolin \& Černý, 2002), using $2 \mathrm{~K}$ atoms, $1 \mathrm{Rb}$ atom and a citrate anion as fragments. A Le Bail fit yielded $R_{\mathrm{wp}}=3.73 \%$. Initial refinement did not include the water molecule, and yielded an acceptable fit $\left(R_{\mathrm{wp}}=4.8 \%\right)$, but the $U_{\text {iso }}$ values of the C atoms in the central part of the molecule were relatively large $\left(\sim 0.10 \AA^{2}\right)$. The bond-valence sums of the cations were, however, far too low, showing that the water molecule was indeed present. It was inserted in the position from the known monohydrate structures.

