The structure was refined by the Rietveld method using $G S A S-I I$ (Toby \& Von Dreele, 2013). The hydrogen atoms were included in fixed positions, which were recalculated during the course of the refinement using Materials Studio (Dassault Systems, 2019). All C-C and C-O bond distances and all bond angles were restrained based on previous citrate

\includegraphics[max width=\textwidth, center]{2023_09_22_6ac063e0fb85cfc10dd0g-05_1603_1649_147_1030}\\
$=1.54$ (1) $\AA, \mathrm{C} 3-\mathrm{C} 6=1.55$ (1) $\AA, \mathrm{C} 3-\mathrm{O} 17=1.42$ (3) $\AA$, $\mathrm{C}($ carboxyl $)-\mathrm{O}($ carboxyl $)=1.27$ (3) $\AA, \mathrm{C} 1-\mathrm{C} 2-\mathrm{C} 3=\mathrm{C} 3-$ C4-C5 $=115(3)^{\circ}$, all angles about C3 $=109(3)^{\circ}$, carboxyl $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O}=115(3)^{\circ}$, and carboxyl $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O}=130(3)^{\circ}$. Each of the three cation sites was modeled as a mixture of $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{Rb}$; the sums of the site occupancies were constrained to be unity, but the total $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{Rb}$ contents were not constrained/ restrained, to provide an internal consistency check. The $U_{\text {iso }}$ of the atoms in the central and outer portions of the citrate anion were constrained to be equal, and the $U_{\text {iso }}$ of the hydrogen atoms were constrained to be $1.3 \times$ those of the atoms to which they are attached. The $U_{\text {iso }}$ of the cations were constrained to be equal. A capillary absorption model (fixed $\mu . R=0.84$, calculated using the tool on the $11-\mathrm{BM}$ web site) was included into the refinement. A Chebyschev polynomial function with four coefficients, along with a peak at $13.11^{\circ}$ to model the scattering of the glass capillary, was used to model the background.

Because DFT techniques cannot accommodate disordered systems, three density functional geometry optimizations (with $\mathrm{Rb}$ at each of the three cations sites, and $\mathrm{K}$ at the other two) were carried out using CRYSTAL14 (Dovesi et al., 2014). The basis sets for the $\mathrm{H}, \mathrm{C}, \mathrm{N}$, and $\mathrm{O}$ atoms were those of Gatti et al. (1994), and the basis sets for $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{Rb}$ were those of Peintinger et al. (2013). The calculations were run on eight 2.1 $\mathrm{GHz}$ Xeon cores (each with $6 \mathrm{~Gb} \mathrm{RAM}$ ) of a 304-core Dell Linux cluster at IIT, using $8 k$-points and the B3LYP functional.

Crystal data, data collection and structure refinement details for (II) are summarized in Table 7 (Fig. 8). The same solution and refinement strategy as for (I) was followed. Three density functional geometry optimizations (with $\mathrm{K}$ at each of the three cations sites, and $\mathrm{Rb}$ at the other two) were carried out using CRYSTAL17 (Dovesi et al., 2018) with atom basis sets and computer hardware as described in the previous paragraph.

